controls.plain_english:
For the purpose of KYC policy, a ‘Customer’ is defined as:


   • a person or entity that maintains an account and/or has a business relationship
      with the bank;

   • one on whose behalf the account is maintained (that is, the beneficial owner);


   • beneficiaries of transactions conducted by professional intermediaries, such as
      Stock Brokers, Chartered Accountants, Solicitors etc.

Banks should frame their KYC policies incorporating the following four key elements:

   (a) Customer Acceptance Policy;


    (b) Customer Identification Procedure;
   (c) Monitoring of Transactions; and
   (d) Risk Management.

